Basic Page Layout with <div>

Objective:
--You’ll learn how to use <div> to structure a basic web page into sections like:
1.Header
2.Navigation
3.Main Content
4.Sidebar
5.Footer

Example HTML Code:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Day 11: Page Layout with div</title>
    <style>
      body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
      }
      .header {
        background-color: #4CAF50;
        color: white;
        padding: 20px;
        text-align: center;
      }
      .nav {
        background-color: #f1f1f1;
        padding: 10px;
        text-align: center;
      }
      .main {
        display: flex;
      }
      .content {
        flex: 70%;
        padding: 20px;
      }
      .sidebar {
        flex: 30%;
        background-color: #f4f4f4;
        padding: 20px;
      }
      .footer {
        background-color: #ddd;
        text-align: center;
        padding: 10px;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>

    <div class="header">
      <h1>My Website</h1>
      <p>Day 11: Basic Layout using &lt;div&gt;</p>
    </div>

    <div class="nav">
      <a href="#">Home</a> |
      <a href="#">About</a> |
      <a href="#">Contact</a>
    </div>

    <div class="main">
      <div class="content">
        <h2>Main Content Area</h2>
        <p>This is the main section of the webpage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sidebar">
        <h3>Sidebar</h3>
        <p>Extra content like links or ads can go here.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="footer">
      <p>© 2025 My First Website</p>
    </div>

  </body>
</html>

What You Learn:
--How to divide your page into sections using <div>
--How CSS helps layout these sections side-by-side or stacked
--Basics of flexbox layout with .main
